\f1\b \cf2 1. Vitamin C / Sodium Ascorbate [{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12772021/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 1}}]\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The Hypothalamic Pump
\f0\b0 : The hypothalamus contains some of the highest concentrations of Vitamin C in the human body. It relies on a specific transporter (
\f1\b SVCT2
\f0\b0 ) to actively pump ascorbate across the blood-brain barrier. [{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4688356/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 1}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4046194/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 2}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4266032/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 3}}]\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Neuroinflammatory Mitigation
\f0\b0 : Sodium ascorbate works as a direct electron donor. It neutralizes the microglial reactive oxygen species (ROS) that drive neuroinflammation during neurodegenerative processes like Parkinson's disease. [{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://books.rsc.org/books/monograph/1887/chapter/2473991/Vitamin-C-Ascorbic-Acid"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 1}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0026049525000307"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 2}}]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs32 \cf2 2. DMSO (Dimethyl Sulfoxide) [{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.researchgate.net/publication/353752965_Effects_of_Vitamin_C_and_Dimethylsulfoxide_Dmso_on_Neuro-Behaviour_Apoptosis_and_oxidative_stress_in_ischaemic_stroke_induced_rats"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 1}}]\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The Permeability Driver
\f0\b0 : In neurodegenerative research, DMSO is rarely used just as an inactive solvent. It is a powerful penetrant that alters cell membrane lipid configurations, allowing other therapeutic compounds to cross the blood-brain barrier. [{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3960278/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 1}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://patents.google.com/patent/WO2012045136A1/en"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 2}}]\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Direct Microglial Suppression
\f0\b0 : At low concentrations, DMSO acts as a potent free-radical scavenger. It down-regulates the 
\f1\b NF-\uc0\u954 B
\f0\b0  signaling pathway, directly reducing the production of pro-inflammatory cytokines (like TNF-\uc0\u945  and IL-6) inside activated microglial cells. [{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6197677/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 1}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11117631/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 2}}]\
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf2 \cb4 EDTA (Ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid)
\f0\b0 \cb1  functions as a high-affinity 
\f1\b heavy metal chelator
\f0\b0  in neuroprotection and neurotoxicology research. Its primary mechanism involves trapping toxic divalent and trivalent cations (such as lead, cadmium, aluminum, and free iron) that accumulate in brain tissues like the 
\f1\b hypothalamus
\f0\b0 , preventing them from driving chronic microglial activation and subsequent neuroinflammation. [{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://go.gale.com/ps/i.do?id=GALE%7CA165167530&sid=googleScholar&v=2.1&it=r&linkaccess=abs&issn=&p=AONE&sw=w"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 1}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://5.imimg.com/data5/SELLER/Doc/2021/3/UY/CE/XE/303480/chelated-edta-mixture.pdf"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 2}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/40b0/a31325a7e3c61d19db35c555d060cf2c9d86.pdf"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 3}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.researchgate.net/post/Protein_extraction_with_without_EDTA"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 4}}]\

\fs28 \

\f1\b\fs40 The Biological Mechanisms of EDTA in the Brain\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\fs32 \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Disruption of the Neurotoxic Cascade
\f0\b0 : Heavy metals act as catalyst triggers for massive oxidative stress in the brain. They activate microglial cells, which produce pro-inflammatory cytokines (like TNF-\uc0\u945  and IL-1\u946 ) that lead to neurodegeneration. By binding these metals into stable, water-soluble complexes, EDTA cuts off the source of this inflammatory loop. [{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.laballey.com/chemicals/acids/edta?srsltid=AfmBOor_sTi9uEejNFxzaUXB7B4JHOfNVl7SBzAcrY7s7ybGFYd5gleq"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 1}}]\
\ls4\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The Blood-Brain Barrier Challenge
\f0\b0 : Standard EDTA (like Disodium EDTA) is highly polar and struggles to cross the intact blood-brain barrier (BBB). Consequently, neurodegenerative research often utilizes 
\f1\b Calcium Disodium EDTA (CaNa
\f4 \uc0\u8322 
\f1 EDTA)
\f0\b0  to prevent the depletion of systemic calcium, or pairs chelation with membrane-permeabilizing agents like 
\f1\b DMSO
\f0\b0 \
\pard\tx566\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
