\f1\b\fs40 \cf2 Part 1: What Causes Narcolepsy? (The Pathological Chain)\

\f0\b0\fs32 Your datasets trace the etiology of Narcolepsy Type 1 (NT1) along a distinct multi-step biological continuum:\

\fs28 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2 \cf2 [Genetic/Environmental Trigger] 
\f5 \uc0\u9472 \u9472 
\f2 > [Auto-Immune T-Cell Activation] \
                                                  
\f5 \uc0\u9474 
\f2 \
                                                  v\
[Hypothalamic Loss (Orexin Destroyed)] <
\f5 \uc0\u9472 \u9472 
\f2  [Microglial Inflammation]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0 \cf2 \

\f1\b\fs32 1. The Core Deficit: Hypothalamic Orexin Wiping\

\f0\b0 The foundational cause is the sudden, catastrophic loss of roughly 70,000 neurons in the lateral hypothalamus that produce 
\f1\b orexin (hypocretin)
\f0\b0 \'97the neuropeptides responsible for locking the brain's sleep-wake switch into an awake state. When these are missing, the REM-sleep cycle fragments and leaks into waking hours, causing 
\f1\b cataplexy
\f0\b0  (sudden muscle weakness) and profound daytime sleepiness.\

\fs28 \

\f1\b\fs32 2. The Root Driver: Auto-Immune Mimicry\

\f0\b0 The data links this cellular destruction to an auto-immune response. Highly specific immune cells (CD4+ and CD8+ T-cells) mistake the surface proteins of orexin neurons for foreign pathogens. This is frequently triggered by a phenomenon called 
\f1\b molecular mimicry
\f0\b0 , where a routine winter infection (like the H1N1 influenza strain or 
\f3\i Streptococcus
\f0\i0  bacteria) leaves behind antibodies that cross-react with hypothalamic tissues.\

\fs28 \

\f1\b\fs32 3. The Local Agent: Microglial Neuroinflammation\

\f0\b0 Once the immune system tags the hypothalamus, local 
\f1\b microglial cells
\f0\b0  become chronically activated. As observed across your deep corpus text blocks, these microglia release a flood of destructive pro-inflammatory cytokines (
\f1\b TNF-\uc0\u945 , IL-1\u946 , and IL-6
\f0\b0 ). This specific inflammatory microenvironment drives local oxidative stress, resulting in the apoptosis of orexin-producing neurons.\

\fs28 \
